# Prompt 2: iOS Translation Architect

Run this prompt SECOND, after reviewing the Cartographer's output in `output/`.
It reads the documentation and produces the iOS app design + phased implementation plan.
The output goes to the `design/` directory.

## Pre-requisites

- Prompt 1 (Cartographer) has been run and output verified
- The `output/` directory contains all expected files (check output/MANIFEST.md)

## The Prompt

```
You are a senior iOS architect specializing in camera pipelines, Metal GPU programming, and Swift concurrency. Design a native iOS/Swift app that replicates the functionality documented in the audit files.

<objective>
Read the audit documentation in output/ and design a native iOS app (iOS 26+, Metal 4, SwiftUI) with a phased implementation plan. Each phase must produce something testable. Preserve behavioral contracts and edge cases from the Android codebase. Address iOS-specific concerns the audit cannot anticipate.

Two core missions:
1. FRAME DELIVERY PIPELINE — Camera → Metal GPU processing → fan-out to C++ consumers (OpenCV) for ML/CV
2. CAMERA CHARACTERISTIC CONTROL SURFACE — Full manual control of focus, AWB, AE, ISO, exposure, zoom

Work only from the audit documentation. Do not read Android source code.
</objective>

<context>
Start with output/06-architecture-brief.md (entry point), then output/02-api-contract.md, then maps and cards as needed. See output/MANIFEST.md for the full file index.

The audit may have gaps. Make provisional choices with stated assumptions, flag in design/07-open-questions.md. Don't block the design on missing data.
</context>

<reference-architecture>
ARCHITECTURE — "Sandwich" pattern:
- TOP: SwiftUI (@Observable ViewModel, never touches buffers)
- MIDDLE: UIViewRepresentable + MTKView (bridge)
- BOTTOM: CameraEngine (Swift actor or class) + C++ interop

HARD REQUIREMENTS:
1. Zero-copy: CVMetalTextureCacheCreateTextureFromImage for CVPixelBuffer → MTLTexture. Create cache ONCE, reuse per-frame.
2. Memory retention: CVBufferRetain before async C++ handoff, CVBufferRelease after. Without this, camera recycles buffer mid-processing.
3. Back-pressure: AsyncStream with .bufferingNewest(1). Drops old frames automatically, keeps memory flat.
4. Preview: Draw Metal output to MTKView, not AVCaptureVideoPreviewLayer (which shows raw feed). Phase 1a may use preview layer temporarily.

CONCURRENCY (Swift 6 compile-time isolation):
| Component | Isolation | Why |
| UI | @MainActor | Receive only simple view states |
| Camera | Serial DispatchQueue | AVFoundation requirement. Hand off to actors immediately. |
| ML/CV | @globalActor (@MLProcessor) | Compiler prevents cross-boundary calls |
| Metal Renderer | nonisolated methods | System calls draw() on its own schedule |

SENDABLE: Keep buffers on one queue. Only Sendable result structs cross actor boundaries. CVPixelBuffer → raw pointer → cv::Mat → OpenCV processing → all on one queue. If buffers must cross boundaries, Swift 6's `sending` annotation (SE-0430) is cleaner than @unchecked Sendable.

C++ INTEROP: Prefer direct Swift-C++ interop (Swift 5.9+). Fall back to ObjC++ only for unsupported C++ features. The C++ layer uses OpenCV (portable). Zero-copy: CVPixelBufferGetBaseAddress → cv::Mat wrapping pointer.

AVAILABLE FRAMEWORKS (iOS 26+):
- Metal 4: ML+graphics integration, improved command encoding
- MetalFX: Temporal upscaling, denoising
- VTFrameProcessor (VideoToolbox): Frame processing with configurable effects, Metal command buffer variant, returns AsyncSequence. Evaluate for standard transforms (color conversion, resize) before writing custom shaders.
- Swift-C++ interop: Direct header import via Clang modules
</reference-architecture>

<constraints>
- iOS 26+, Swift 6, Metal 4. No backward-compatibility shims.
- Evaluate VTFrameProcessor for standard transforms before custom Metal shaders.
- SwiftUI primary, UIKit only for MTKView/AVCaptureVideoPreviewLayer.
- Prefer direct Swift-C++ interop. Assess OpenCV header compatibility with Clang modules.
- Swift 6 actor isolation. @MainActor for UI, @globalActor for ML, serial queue for camera.
- Error handling and camera controls from Phase 1, not bolted on later.
- Zero-copy throughout. Frame dropping via AsyncStream, not queuing.
</constraints>

<deliverables>

DELIVERABLE 0 — GAP ANALYSIS

Write design/00-gap-analysis.md FIRST, before designing anything:
| Gap/Risk | Audit file | What's missing or wrong | Impact on design | Provisional choice? |
- Missing information, architectural risks, ambiguities, contradictions
- Make provisional choices where possible, flag blocking gaps

DELIVERABLE 1 — CONCURRENCY, STATE, AND ERROR DESIGN

Write design/01-concurrency-and-state.md:

### Concurrency Architecture
| Android construct (from audit) | Swift equivalent | Why this choice |
- Map every L2 threading invariant to a compile-time enforcement mechanism
- AsyncStream .bufferingNewest(1) for frame delivery
- Sendable strategy: buffers on one queue, results cross boundaries
- Justify every isolation boundary

### State Machine
- Replicate Android state machine using Swift enum + actor
- Add iOS-specific states: WAITING_FOR_PERMISSION
- How state changes propagate to SwiftUI
- Port every L4 edge-case guard with iOS equivalent

### Error & Recovery
- iOS stall watchdog equivalent
- AVCaptureSession failure modes and recovery
- Port every L4 error guard

### iOS-Specific Failure Modes
Design handling for (these have NO Android equivalent):
- ProcessInfo.ThermalState (degrade resolution/frame rate)
- AVCaptureDevice.SystemPressureState (reduce capture quality)
- Multi-app camera conflicts
- AVCaptureSession runtime errors
- Permission denial/revocation mid-session

### Permissions
- NSCameraUsageDescription, PHPhotoLibrary authorization
- Integrated with state machine, graceful denial handling

DELIVERABLE 2 — METAL PIPELINE DESIGN

Write design/02-metal-pipeline.md:

### Pipeline Architecture
- Evaluate VTFrameProcessor for each processing step first
- Document which transforms it handles vs which need custom shaders
- Custom shaders: compute vs fragment vs MPS, with justification
- Pipeline topology (Mermaid)

### Texture Specification
| Stage | MTLPixelFormat | Dimensions | Usage flags | Storage mode |

### Color Space / HDR
- SDR or HDR? Recommendation with justification.
- Texture format implications (BGRA8Unorm vs RGBA16Float)

### Zero-Copy Path
- CVPixelBuffer → MTLTexture → MTKView
- CVPixelBuffer → cv::Mat → OpenCV (CPU path)
- Fan-out: how processed frames reach preview AND C++ consumers

### Shader Translation
- Each GLSL shader → Metal Shading Language equivalent
- Formats, constant buffers, thread group sizing

### Profiling Strategy
- os_signpost intervals for each pipeline stage
- Frame budget breakdown (e.g., 33ms at 30fps: capture <2ms, compute <8ms, display <4ms)
- Thresholds: acceptable vs degraded vs failing
- Instruments templates: Metal System Trace, Allocations, Time Profiler

DELIVERABLE 3 — INTEGRATION AND CONTROLS DESIGN

Write design/03-integration-and-controls.md:

### C++ / OpenCV Integration
- Assess Swift-C++ interop compatibility for OpenCV headers
- If compatible: direct Swift → C++ calls. If not: thin ObjC++ bridge.
- OpenCV iOS setup (CocoaPods, SPM, or xcframework)
- Zero-copy handoff: CVPixelBufferLockBaseAddress → GetBaseAddress → cv::Mat → process → unlock
- C++ portability (from audit's cpp-sinks card)

### Results Return Path
Trace this concrete scenario through the entire stack:
"OpenCV detects an object at (x=0.3, y=0.5, w=0.2, h=0.15), confidence 0.87, label 'cell'."
Show: C++ type → Swift Sendable struct → thread transitions → SwiftUI overlay.
Design os_signpost intervals so Instruments shows where inference latency ends and UI latency begins.

### Camera Device Discovery
- AVCaptureDevice.DiscoverySession
- Front/back/wide/ultra-wide selection
- Device switching and session reconfiguration
- Capability querying per device

### Camera Controls
| Characteristic | Android API (audit) | iOS API (AVCaptureDevice) | Differences | Constraints |
- lockForConfiguration/unlockForConfiguration pattern
- Supported range querying
- Control conflicts (manual exposure → AE off)

### What NOT to Port
Items from the audit that are Android-only and should be omitted:
| Item | Why it's Android-only | Safe to omit? |

DELIVERABLE 4 — PHASED IMPLEMENTATION PLAN

Write design/04-implementation-phases.md:

Six phases. Each produces a testable app. Each MUST include a file tree with each file's responsibility and which design doc section it implements.

### Phase 1a — Camera Capture + State Machine + Lifecycle
- SwiftUI scaffold with actor-based concurrency from day one
- Permission flow, AVCaptureSession setup, device discovery
- Raw preview (AVCaptureVideoPreviewLayer — temporary)
- Full state machine including WAITING_FOR_PERMISSION
- Error detection: interruption handler, system pressure monitoring
- Background/foreground lifecycle, basic thermal monitoring

Acceptance: permission handling, preview works, camera switching, state machine logs match design, interruption recovery.

File tree: [REQUIRED]

### Phase 1b — Camera Controls
- All controls wired to AVCaptureDevice APIs
- UI for each control
- Capability querying, control interactions

Acceptance: every control adjusts real parameter, ranges correct per device, conflicts handled.

File tree: [REQUIRED]

### Phase 2 — Metal Processing Pipeline
- Replace preview layer with Metal render path
- CVPixelBuffer → MTLTexture via cache (zero-copy)
- Metal compute shaders / VTFrameProcessor for transforms
- MTKView display, processing configuration API
- os_signpost instrumentation

Acceptance: processed preview, correct transforms, stable frame rate, signpost timing breakdown.

File tree: [REQUIRED — include .metal files]

### Phase 3 — C++ / OpenCV Integration + Fan-Out
- C++ integration (direct Swift or ObjC++ bridge)
- OpenCV framework setup
- Zero-copy handoff: CVPixelBuffer → cv::Mat
- Fan-out: preview + ML sink + CV sink simultaneously
- AsyncStream back-pressure, results return to SwiftUI
- os_signpost on return path

Acceptance: C++ consumer receives frames, memory stable, slow consumer drops frames, results in SwiftUI overlay.

File tree: [REQUIRED]

### Phase 4 — Performance + Resilience
- Frame pacing (triple-buffering/ring buffer)
- GPU readback optimization
- Profiling with Instruments
- Thermal throttling response, system pressure response
- Performance thresholds enforced

Acceptance: measured latency, no frame drops, graceful thermal degradation.

File tree: [REQUIRED]

### Phase 5 — Capture + Recording
- Still capture (AVCapturePhotoOutput, EXIF)
- Photo library permission
- Video recording (AVAssetWriter, audio sync)
- All recording edge-case guards from audit
- Mid-recording error handling, background teardown

Acceptance: EXIF correct, recording clean start/stop, audio synced, background-safe.

File tree: [REQUIRED]

### Phase 6 — Parity + Polish
- Feature parity audit against output/02-api-contract.md
- UI refinement to match Android screenshots
- Remaining edge cases verified
- Final performance pass

Acceptance: every API method mapped or documented as N/A, UI matches, edge cases verified.

DELIVERABLE 5 — DESIGN DECISIONS LOG

Write design/05-decisions-log.md:
| # | Decision | Alternatives | Chosen because | Audit reference | Reversibility |

DELIVERABLE 6 — RISK REGISTER

Write design/06-risks.md:
| Risk | Phase | Likelihood | Impact | Mitigation | Audit L4 ref |

DELIVERABLE 7 — OPEN QUESTIONS

Write design/07-open-questions.md:
- Audit gaps with provisional choices and stated assumptions
- Architecture choices with no clear winner
- iOS-specific concerns not in the audit
- Performance targets needing definition
</deliverables>

<tool-usage>
Read: files in output/ and design/
Write: files in design/ only
Do not read Android source code — work from audit documentation.
</tool-usage>

<quality-gates>
- Every L2 invariant from audit has an iOS enforcement mechanism
- Every L4 guard has an iOS equivalent or explicit justification for omission
- Every API contract method is mapped or documented as N/A
- Each phase has a concrete file tree and testable acceptance criteria
- VTFrameProcessor evaluated before custom shaders proposed
- Buffers confined to one queue; only Sendable results cross boundaries
- Profiling strategy has os_signpost intervals and frame budget thresholds
- iOS-specific failure modes designed for
- Decisions log captures significant choices with alternatives
</quality-gates>
```
